{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17611426","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17611426"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:10:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16211"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16211","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16211"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.38,0.42,0,0.21,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8902"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115381"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8902"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16211"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97384"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8402"},{"type":"tags","id":"10640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21182"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21185"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115381"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe composition of breast tissue varies throughout a woman\u0027s life, particularly in response to hormonal changes and reproductive status.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the relative proportions of glandular and stromal tissue in different breast states?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active breast has 1:2 gland-to-stroma ratio, lactating breast is mostly glandular, atrophic breast is mostly stromal","Active breast has 2:1 gland-to-stroma ratio, lactating breast is mostly glandular, atrophic breast is mostly stromal","Active breast has 1:1 gland-to-stroma ratio, lactating breast is mostly stromal, atrophic breast is mostly glandular","Active breast has 1:1 gland-to-stroma ratio, lactating breast is mostly glandular, atrophic breast is mostly stromal","Active breast has 2:1 gland-to-stroma ratio, lactating breast is mostly stromal, atrophic breast is mostly glandular"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct description is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive breast has a 1:2 gland-to-stroma ratio, the lactating breast is predominantly glandular tissue, and the atrophic breast is predominantly stromal tissue\u003C/strong\u003E. This reflects the normal physiological changes that occur in breast tissue throughout a woman\u0027s life.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003E2:1 gland-to-stroma ratio in active breast tissue\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate more glandular than stromal tissue, which is incorrect for non-lactating breast. A \u003Cstrong\u003E1:1 gland-to-stroma ratio\u003C/strong\u003E does not accurately reflect the predominance of stromal tissue in the active breast. Having \u003Cstrong\u003Emostly stromal tissue during lactation\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the physiological need for increased glandular tissue during milk production. Having \u003Cstrong\u003Emostly glandular tissue in the atrophic breast\u003C/strong\u003E contradicts the natural involution that occurs post-menopause. During pregnancy and lactation, breast tissue undergoes significant proliferation of glandular elements under hormonal influence. After menopause, glandular tissue atrophies while stromal and fatty tissue remains, leading to the predominantly stromal composition of the atrophic breast.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The ratio of glandular tissue to stroma in the breast varies with reproductive status, with glandular tissue predominating during lactation.","In the non-lactating adult breast, glandular and stromal tissues are present in roughly equal proportions.","Post-menopausal breast tissue becomes atrophic with stromal tissue predominating over glandular tissue."],"references":["Zucca-Matthes G, Urban C, Vallejo A. Anatomy of the nipple and breast ducts. Gland Surg. 2016 Feb;5(1):32-6. doi: 10.3978/j.issn.2227-684X.2015.05.10. PMID: 26855906; PMCID: PMC4716863.","Wiseman BS, Werb Z. Stromal effects on mammary gland development and breast cancer. Science. 2002 May 10;296(5570):1046-9. doi: 10.1126/science.1067431. PMID: 12004111; PMCID: PMC2788989","Shekhar MP, Werdell J, Santner SJ, Pauley RJ, Tait L. Breast stroma plays a dominant regulatory role in breast epithelial growth and differentiation: implications for tumor development and progression. Cancer Res. 2001 Feb 15;61(4):1320-6. PMID: 11245428","Arendt LM, Rudnick JA, Keller PJ, Kuperwasser C. Stroma in breast development and disease. Semin Cell Dev Biol. 2010 Feb;21(1):11-8. doi: 10.1016/j.semcdb.2009.10.003. Epub 2009 Oct 24. PMID: 19857593; PMCID: PMC2823823","Javed A, Lteif A. Development of the human breast. Semin Plast Surg. 2013 Feb;27(1):5-12. doi: 10.1055/s-0033-1343989. PMID: 24872732; PMCID: PMC3706056","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97384"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16211"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97384","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97384"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T14:18:59+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T14:20:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":